KW  - Wage differentials
KW  - Human capital
KW  - Implicit insurance
KW  - Economic development
AB  - This paper explores the role of wage structure as implicit insurance on human capital. It illustrates how smaller wage differentials in the developed world can be welfare-enhancing by acting as implicit insurance while larger wage differentials in underdeveloped countries make investments in human capital riskier. In other words, with smaller wage differentials, the students in a developed country are insured against poor educational outcomes through the existence of well-paid alternative employments which are not present in the economy of a less developed country. This result arises as multiple equilibria in a general equilibrium model when there are no insurance markets for human capital.
